# Server-Side Test Scripts

## The Rule

Every new system, feature, or bug fix that touches backend logic MUST include a **runnable server-side test script** (PHP or shell). No exceptions. Tests run on the server via CLI, never in the browser.

## When to Create a Test

- Building a new system or subsystem (email, drive, sync, cron, etc.)
- Fixing a bug in an existing system
- Adding a new integration (OAuth, webhook, API, etc.)
- Changing database schema or migrations
- Modifying cron jobs or background processes
- Touching encryption, auth, or credentials

## Test Script Requirements

### Format
- **PHP** (`#!/usr/bin/env php`) or **Shell** (`#!/bin/bash`) -- whichever matches the system under test
- Must run from CLI only (`php_sapi_name() !== 'cli'` guard for PHP)
- Must accept `--help` with usage instructions
- Must accept `--verbose` for extra debug output

### Required CLI Flags
- `--help` -- usage instructions
- `--verbose` -- extra debug output (stack traces, raw responses)
- `--skip-send` (or equivalent) -- skip destructive/external operations
- `--only=group1,group2` -- run only specific test categories
- `--smoke` -- quick health check mode (connectivity + config only, no business logic)
- `--json` -- output results as JSON (for automation/monitoring)

### Structure
- Use the cron bootstrap (`require_once __DIR__ . '/../cron/bootstrap.php'`) so `.env` and autoloader are available
- Accept credentials via CLI args (`--email=`, `--password=`, etc.), never hardcode them in the script
- Group tests by category with section headers (`--- N. CATEGORY ---`)
- Each test is a named callable with pass/fail/warn outcome and elapsed time

### Pre-Flight Checks (run before any tests)
- Verify required PHP extensions are loaded (`imap`, `redis`, `openssl`, `mbstring`, etc.)
- Verify required services are reachable (DB, Redis, IMAP, SMTP)
- Verify sufficient disk space in temp and storage directories
- Verify required config values are present and non-empty
- If any pre-flight fails, abort early with a clear message -- do not run tests against a broken environment

### Logging
- Every test run writes a timestamped log file to `storage/logs/` (e.g. `email-test-20260409-143022.log`)
- Log format: `[HH:MM:SS] [PASS|FAIL|WARN] Test Name (Xms)`
- On failure, log the error message and (in verbose mode) file + line
- Print a summary at the end: passed, failed, warnings, total
- List all failed tests with their error messages in the summary
- Use color-coded terminal output: green for PASS, red for FAIL, yellow for WARN

### Coverage Depth
- Test the full chain, not just one layer (e.g. DB -> Service -> SMTP -> IMAP, not just "can I connect")
- Test error paths: what happens with bad credentials, missing files, invalid data
- Test roundtrips: encrypt then decrypt, schedule then retrieve, send then verify in Sent folder
- Test permissions: directory writable, crontab entry exists, config values present
- Clean up all test data at the end (remove test DB rows, temp files)

### Safety / Non-Destructive Guarantee
- Tests MUST NEVER modify, delete, or corrupt production data
- All test data must use a recognizable prefix (e.g. `[FLOWONE-TEST]` in subjects, `flowone_test_` in filenames) so it can never be confused with real data
- Cleanup MUST run even if tests fail -- use try/finally or register a shutdown handler
- Register `pcntl_signal` handlers (SIGINT, SIGTERM) to run cleanup if the script is killed mid-run
- Tests must be **idempotent** -- safe to run 10 times in a row with identical results

### Timeout Protection
- Individual tests should have a timeout (default 30 seconds, configurable)
- If a test hangs (e.g. SMTP connection to a dead host), it must not block the entire suite
- Use `set_time_limit()` or `pcntl_alarm()` per test in PHP, or `timeout` command in shell

### Exit Code
- Exit `0` on all pass
- Exit `1` on any failure

## File Location

Place test scripts in `tests/` next to the system they test:

```
email/backend/tests/email-system-test.php
email/backend/tests/drive-system-test.php
email/backend/tests/sync-system-test.php
```

## Run Command Template

Always provide the exact server run command in the script header:

```
/usr/local/lsws/lsphp83/bin/php /var/www/vps-email/backend/tests/SCRIPT.php --email=USER --password=PASS --verbose
```

## What NOT to Do

- Do NOT create browser-based test pages
- Do NOT hardcode passwords or secrets in the test file
- Do NOT leave test data in the database after the script finishes
- Do NOT skip logging -- every test must be traceable after the fact
- Do NOT write tests that only check "can I connect" -- test the actual business logic end-to-end
- Do NOT let one hanging test block the entire suite -- always use timeouts
- Do NOT create test data without a recognizable prefix -- it must be distinguishable from real data
